title: For Sale/Trade:  HK VP9 V1 "CUSTOM STIPPLE JOB" LIKE NEW.....
postcontent:
I HAVE A LIKE NEW HK VP9 VARIANT 1 UP FOR GRABS. THE STIPPLE JOB IS THIS HK IS OUTSTANDING AND WAS MUCH NEEDED AS THE STOCK TEXURE IS WAY TO SLICK. 110RDS DOWN RANGE. COMES WITH BOX, 2 MAGS, PAPERS ECT... PM OR TEXT REDACTED FOR FASTEST RESPONSE... IVE HAD TONS OF PEOPLE INTERESTED BUT NOTHING SET IN STONE...
In development for more than four years, the VP9 is Heckler & Koch’s latest handgun and the first striker fired HK since the renowned P7 series pistols were introduced in the 1980s.

Experience gained by HK engineers with the recent P30 pistol had a direct influence on the design of the VP9, but the VP9 breaks new ground with its integration of a unique striker firing system with an enhanced HK “light pull” trigger. The net result is trigger quality unequaled in any production striker fired handgun.

HK pioneered the first striker fired handguns, producing both the VP70 and P7 series, designs that impacted several models by HK competitors. But a superior trigger has eluded most striker fired pistol designs. The VP9 trigger surpasses those found on competitors. It has a short, light take-up with a solid, single action type break followed by a short positive reset.

The VP9 trigger has a consistent pre-travel pull with a positive wall/crisp break. Typically, striker fired guns have a pre-travel pull that increases in weight as you go through the trigger stroke. With the VP9, you have a less than noticeable pre-travel pull until the trigger reaches the engagement point of the fire control parts prior to trigger break.

The VP9 uses HK’s ergonomic handgun grip design that includes three changeable backstraps and six side panels— accommodating all hand sizes. Molded finger grooves in the front of the pistol’s grip also instinctively position an operator’s hand for optimal shooting. Only HK handguns have such a customized grip.

Although influenced by other HK models, the VP9 has all the hallmarks of the latest, state-of-the-art handgun. All controls are completely ambidextrous. Slide releases are present on both sides of the frame and the magazine release can be easily activated by left- or right-handed shooters.

A new feature is HK’s patented charging supports — simple components that are mounted on each side of the rear of the slide and provide better gripping leverage for racking the slide rearward. The charging supports speed reloading and make operating the VP9 easier for shooters with reduced hand strength. The VP pistols uses the proven P30 steel magazine; 15 and 10-round capacity available.

The VP9 has an extended Picatinny MIL-STD-1913 rail molded into its polymer frame for mounting lights and accessories. The rail has been tested and certified to handle mounted accessories up to 5.6 ounces.

The VP9’s proprietary captive flat recoil spring helps reduce the recoil forces effecting the operator and the handgun, improving shooter control during rapid firing and prolonging component service life.

HK’s famous cold hammer forged barrel — made from cannon grade steel — ensures long service life. Similar HK barrels on 9 mm P30 models have fired more than 90,000 rounds in endurance tests in 2010. The polygonal bore profile, with no traditional lands-and-grooves rifling, contributes to longer service life as well as a slight increase in muzzle velocity.

The VP9’s machined steel slide is protected from corrosion and wear by HK’s hostile environment finish and all metal components, including springs and pins have superior metallurgy.

VP pistols are made in Heckler & Koch’s Oberndorf factory in southwest Germany. The VP9 is well-suited for civilian sport shooting, security, military, and law enforcement use.

Covered by Heckler & Koch’s limited lifetime warranty, the HK VP9 is a solid design engineered with the famous long-term durability that make HK products especially cost-effective when subjected to total life cycle cost analysis. Suggested retail price of the VP9 is $719 with projected availability of July 2014.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Heckler & Koch HK P2000 .40 S&W, 2 holsters, 2 mags, box...
location: Summerville / Dorchester Rd., Charleston, South Carolina
postcontent:
This is the LEM edition of the .40 HK P2000. You'll get the gun, two right-handed holsters (IWB and modular), two magazines, a .40 brass brush, four interchangeable backstraps for sizing, the original HK gun case, two mags full of hollow points, and a bag of about 50 or so FMJ rounds. 

The trigger pull is the LEM edition, which means once you chamber a round, you will feel only ONE trigger pull from the first round to the last - a long, medium weight (not sure the weight) trigger pull. You carry it with one in the pipe - the long trigger pull makes this the preferred method of carry for this weapon.

This gun is fully ambidextrous - slide release and mag release on both sides. The only controls on this gun are the slide release, the mag release, and the trigger. No safety, no decocker needed. Again - carry it just like you would a DAO revolver - one in the pipe, ready to go. It has a lighter pull than a DAO, but still enough to be safe with one in the pipe - making this gun very much a "ready for action" fighting weapon.

This gun has been cleaned after every range day, and never exposed to rain, saltwater, dirt, etc. It has approximately 6,000 rounds on it, and feeds and operates flawlessly (I have never experienced a misfeed. I shoot Winchester, Blazer and Georgia Arms reloads, and occasional other brands). The mag springs / internal springs are very strong, and the gun needs no servicing to my knowlege.

I'm selling this with my right-handed draw CrossBreed Ohai modular velcro-backed holster, which is ideal for carry in a Maxpedition or 5.11 tactical concealed carry bag, or installation in a vehicle compartment. I carry every day in a 5.11 tactical bag, and the holster works great, with a very easy draw and good retention. I have cut down the leather on the holster to enable full thumb engagement around the backstrap without getting your thumb jammed up on the holster.

I'm also selling a leather IWB holster that works reasonably well. I mostly use this holster when I need to throw the gun in the glove compartment or similar situations, but it works OK for IWB carry every now and again. 

The mags are a 12 round and a 10 round mag. 

I will only sell this gun to you if you are a CWP holder, military member or retiree, DoD clearance-holder, police officer or person of similar verifiable reputation, or can bring such a person along when you buy to vouch for your lawful and responsible character.

title: For Sale:   Winchester mod. 1886, short bar, Rare Browning Bro
postcontent: "Reduced for about 10 days or until something else sells" Consider Partial Trades !!! ." Winchester Collectors Don't miss this one. " This is an unusual & Very RARE Win. 86 in 40-82 cal. short barrel . Barrel is 22 inch octagonal with a short tube and a steel cres. Butt plate. Circa 1897-98.It has a dove tailed front sight. A Win. collector told me that there's one similar to it in 38-55 cal. in John Madis's Winchester book, 1st edition on page 319. It has 22 inch oct. Bar and steel Cres. Butt plate. This was said to be a special order. Another Win. Collector emailed me saying that this gun could have been modified and marketed by Browning Bros. Odgen, Utah. since the top of the barrel is marked Browning Bros Co. He had never seen one marked like this. I would guess that there are very few 86s out there marked like this and in pretty nice condition. Short barreled configuration and Browning marked, " NOT MANY AROUND ". I'm almost talking myself into buying it. I'm selling this gun for a friend who has had it stored away for many moons and now because of age and health is letting some things go. I just googled Browning Arms Co. and got a little history. In 1852 Jonathan Browning established his gunsmith shop in Ogden, Utah. Jonathan died in 1872 at which time his oldest son, John Moses Browning took over and along with his brothers formed Browning Bros.Co. in Ogden. They had both a gunsmith shop and a retail store.Any guns that they sold or customized contained their mark or as they say in the west their brand. Google Browning Arms Co. and read the whole history.

title: For Sale:  Lefever 12 Gauge Side by Side 1902
postcontent:
Firearm Antique Lefever Double Barrel Shotgun
This antique Lefever Arms Co. Model H Grade has a 410 conversion kit professionally fitted in the 12 gauge barrels by the previous owner and Lefever collector. Conversion kit worth $200 + by itself. The conversion can easily be removed and restored to its original condition. The barrels are made of Damascus steel and all metal pieces show a nice patina. Features Damascus steel barrels, flat matted rib with doll’s head extension, smooth hardwood pistol-grip style stock and forearm, 28” barrels, steel receiver with break open action (breech loaded), double triggers, front brass bead sights, thumb breech lever & safety, and the original Lefever Arms Company butt-plate. Overall length of 44 ½”. There are patent markings of 1872, 85, 86, & 87 on the underside of the receiver. SN on trigger guard of 44XXX would indicate a DOM year of 1902. Lefever’s are difficult to grade, due to their age and scarcity, however this has been professionally graded at 90%, which is a high grade for a gun this old as the steel patina, and wood are in excellent, almost pristine, condition. A fine gun for the Lefever Collector. Used.

title: For Sale/Trade:  HK VP9 V1 W/CUSTOM GRIP.... 9MM
postcontent:
I HAVE A LIKE NEW HK VP9 VARIANT 1 UP FOR GRABS. THE STIPPLE JOB IS THIS HK IS OUTSTANDING AND WAS MUCH NEEDED AS THE STOCK TEXURE IS WAY TO SLICK. 110RDS DOWN RANGE. COMES WITH BOX, 2 MAGS, PAPERS ECT... PM OR TEXT REDACTED FOR FASTEST RESPONSE... IVE HAD TONS OF PEOPLE INTERESTED BUT NOTHING SET IN STONE... AR15 NOT FOR SALE....
In development for more than four years, the VP9 is Heckler & Koch’s latest handgun and the first striker fired HK since the renowned P7 series pistols were introduced in the 1980s.

Experience gained by HK engineers with the recent P30 pistol had a direct influence on the design of the VP9, but the VP9 breaks new ground with its integration of a unique striker firing system with an enhanced HK “light pull” trigger. The net result is trigger quality unequaled in any production striker fired handgun.

HK pioneered the first striker fired handguns, producing both the VP70 and P7 series, designs that impacted several models by HK competitors. But a superior trigger has eluded most striker fired pistol designs. The VP9 trigger surpasses those found on competitors. It has a short, light take-up with a solid, single action type break followed by a short positive reset.

The VP9 trigger has a consistent pre-travel pull with a positive wall/crisp break. Typically, striker fired guns have a pre-travel pull that increases in weight as you go through the trigger stroke. With the VP9, you have a less than noticeable pre-travel pull until the trigger reaches the engagement point of the fire control parts prior to trigger break.

The VP9 uses HK’s ergonomic handgun grip design that includes three changeable backstraps and six side panels— accommodating all hand sizes. Molded finger grooves in the front of the pistol’s grip also instinctively position an operator’s hand for optimal shooting. Only HK handguns have such a customized grip.

Although influenced by other HK models, the VP9 has all the hallmarks of the latest, state-of-the-art handgun. All controls are completely ambidextrous. Slide releases are present on both sides of the frame and the magazine release can be easily activated by left- or right-handed shooters.

A new feature is HK’s patented charging supports — simple components that are mounted on each side of the rear of the slide and provide better gripping leverage for racking the slide rearward. The charging supports speed reloading and make operating the VP9 easier for shooters with reduced hand strength. The VP pistols uses the proven P30 steel magazine; 15 and 10-round capacity available.

The VP9 has an extended Picatinny MIL-STD-1913 rail molded into its polymer frame for mounting lights and accessories. The rail has been tested and certified to handle mounted accessories up to 5.6 ounces.

The VP9’s proprietary captive flat recoil spring helps reduce the recoil forces effecting the operator and the handgun, improving shooter control during rapid firing and prolonging component service life.

HK’s famous cold hammer forged barrel — made from cannon grade steel — ensures long service life. Similar HK barrels on 9 mm P30 models have fired more than 90,000 rounds in endurance tests in 2010. The polygonal bore profile, with no traditional lands-and-grooves rifling, contributes to longer service life as well as a slight increase in muzzle velocity.

The VP9’s machined steel slide is protected from corrosion and wear by HK’s hostile environment finish and all metal components, including springs and pins have superior metallurgy.

VP pistols are made in Heckler & Koch’s Oberndorf factory in southwest Germany. The VP9 is well-suited for civilian sport shooting, security, military, and law enforcement use.

Covered by Heckler & Koch’s limited lifetime warranty, the HK VP9 is a solid design engineered with the famous long-term durability that make HK products especially cost-effective when subjected to total life cycle cost analysis. Suggested retail price of the VP9 is $719 with projected availability of July 2014.
